    <div class="sec-t">About</div>
    <p>Bakklandet is a neighbourhood in Trondheim in Trøndelag county, located on the <strong>east bank of the Nidelva River</strong> within the Østbyen borough, between Bakke Bridge (Bakke bru) to the north and Old Town Bridge (Gamle Bybro) to the south. First settled in the <strong>early 17th century</strong> as Trondheim's first suburb, it developed as a working-class district of narrow streets and timber houses built along the wharves, home to seamen, craftsmen, fishermen, and labourers. In 1718 it was largely destroyed during a Swedish siege and subsequently rebuilt. The neighbourhood is divided into Nedre Bakklandet (Lower) north of Gamle Bybro and Øvre Bakklandet (Upper) to the south.</p>
    <p>In <strong>1965</strong>, Trondheim's city plan proposed demolishing a large section of Bakklandet to build a four-lane motorway connecting Elgeseter gate with Innherredsveien. Local opposition began in 1971 with the formation of Miljøgruppen på Bakklandet; despite the city's environmental council approving depopulation of the neighbourhood in 1974, the motorway plan was shelved by the early 1980s. The campaign's success preserved the 17th–19th century timber buildings that define the area today. Subsequent decades saw middle-class renovation of the wooden houses, transforming Bakklandet into one of Trondheim's most sought-after residential districts.</p>
    <p>Today the neighbourhood contains independent cafés, boutiques, art galleries, and restaurants housed in coloured timber buildings on cobblestone streets. <strong>Baklandet Skydsstasjon</strong> operates in a building dating from 1791 and is among the most-visited establishments. <strong>Trampe</strong>, installed in 1993 on Brubakken hill and widely cited as the world's first mechanised bicycle lift, assists cyclists toward Kristiansten Fortress. A riverside lookout called <strong>Krana</strong>, between Nedre Bakklandet 10 and 18, offers views of the wharf buildings along the Nidelva. Access from the city centre is via Gamle Bybro.</p>
